Perspectives for Sino-American Relations 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations had destabilizing effects on wide parts of Asia.
One year ago, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly pompous "State Visit Plus" in Beijing, from which China had hoped that Trump's anti-Chinese campaign rhetoric would finally belong to the past.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are embroiled in a trade war, and the Trump administration has replaced the "strategic engagement" of the United States with China with "strategic competition."
In addition, the US, European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming one year ago.
Today, there is great uncertainty in financial markets, growth is slowing down in China and Europe, and higher interest rates are beginning to take effect in America.
The uncertainty about the future development of the nuclear negotiations with North Korea also clouds the picture.
What were the prospects for the relations between the USA and China in 2019?
It is likely that an agreement on the reduction of the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions China will make will be reached by March.
An agreement on tariff reductions is also possible by then, although the complexity of the topic could extend the targeted timeframe.
If each tariff were negotiated separately, it could take a year.
If Chinese economic reformers were to adopt a more drastic approach by gradually committing to the abolition of all tariffs and urging Americans to do the same, faster results could be achieved.
This would, however, go against Chinese trade officials who have been trained for decades to give little, let alone everything at once.
The reform of so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively uncomplicated.
Despite this, a reform is something different from how contractual agreements might be interpreted in practice, even if there should be no specific provisions regarding technology transfer.
The protection of intellectual property is, however, extremely problematic.
Previous agreements made under President Barack Obama's administration could be reaffirmed again.
The enforcement or legal action in cases of infringement of rights to intellectual property remains a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism involves subjecting relevant agreements between Chinese and foreign companies to arbitration by international tribunals in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically tasked with enforcing the protection of intellectual property.
Should China raise objections, it could develop its own international arbitration tribunal based in China.
For this to strengthen the international credibility of the arbitration body, it would have to include qualified foreigners.
No one has confidence in Chinese trade courts.
For its own domestic reform needs, China must move towards completely independent trade and civil courts within its judicial system, even if the criminal court remains subject to political control.
The American concerns regarding the state subsidies within the framework of the country's "Made in China 2025" strategy will hardly be resolved.
The fact is that all countries provide some level of state support to their domestic technology sectors, although China does so to the highest degree.
Even if we were to prescribe a maximum level of state support for a particular company, it would be difficult to enforce.
I am not optimistic about reaching an agreement in this area.
Perhaps America simply has to outcompete China by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China offers customs reforms to the rest of the international community.
So China might eventually decide to take the drastic step of agreeing to free trade not only with the USA, but with all member states of the World Trade Organization.
In this way, China would be offered almost irresistible opportunities to position itself as a champion of global free trade and to curb the trend toward protectionism.
In such a turn, China could invite the members of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) to join, thereby overhauling the USA (which withdrew from the free trade agreement as one of the first official acts of Trump's presidency) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably agile when it discovers a political opportunity and market opening.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations about China joining the TPP have decreased since Ministerial Prime Minister Shinzo Abe's recent visit to Beijing.
Given the central strategic challenges vis-à-vis the USA, China is likely to strive in its general foreign and security policy in 2019 to reduce conflicts in its relationships with other countries.
In the relationships with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from the Japanese Coast Guard indicate a clear reduction in Chinese incursions into the East China Sea around the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands.
Also the tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations regarding the South China Sea will be reduced by China through accelerated negotiations of a "Code of Conduct".
Moreover, China seems to have a more relaxed relationship with India following the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China could start moderating its stance towards Taiwan, given the electoral setback suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party of Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen, which advocates independence, in the local and regional elections last month.
This would naturally change radically if the USA continues with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
Incidents at sea continue to occur with the USA in the South China Sea, and the conflict could intensify if the USA more forcefully assert their stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
In the entire Eurasian continent, China will continue to implement its major project "Belt and Road."
In the last months, the initiative in China, however, has caused less political uproar.
Among Chinese officials, there are already discussions about revising certain modalities, following Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota port to China, which triggered negative reactions and raised concerns about the long-term financing sustainability of the Belt and Road initiative.
In 2019, triumphant reports about the Belt and Road initiative may therefore be less frequent.
Furthermore, China is likely to strengthen and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions rather than highlight new institutions of international political diplomacy.
It is likely to continue presenting itself as a new advocate for the WHO and maintain its stance on global climate change as agreed in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
More sober representatives of China's foreign policy establishment believe it is better to focus on the existing mechanisms of the global rule-based system, especially given the USA's consistent disregard for it.
While China tries to stabilize its relations with the USA and reduce tensions in its relationships with other countries, its leadership will likely use 2019 to form a solid judgment about the future of US politics: the implications of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his government, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would in any way alter the new US strategy.
Although they have already concluded that America's stance towards China has fundamentally changed, they are uncertain about the exact form this change takes and whether a fundamental strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is called for.
